node.text:
“You will be challenged during the next four years, but you can do it,” said Academy Superintendent Lt. Gen. Richard Clark. “Take one bite at a time. The first step is completing basic cadet training, and you have already demonstrated you have what it takes to succeed by getting here. I stood where you stand almost 40 years ago and I’m so glad I stuck it out.”

The global COVID-19 pandemic may be on the decline, but the Air Force Academy took no chances when more than 1,100 young men and women reported to the school for basic cadet training, June 24.

The trainees arrived between 7 a.m.-noon, were given facemasks, and immediately tested for the coronavirus.

Check out more on this story at www.usafa.edu.

node.text: Today, cadets march in a Founders Day Parade honoring the legacy of #youracademy. Together, we stand on the foundation built by those who came before us, striving to strengthen that foundation for those who come after us, reinforcing our bonds with a culture of dignity and respect. Being part of the Long Blue Line means being part of something bigger than ourselves, collectively building and bolstering the bridge to the future @usairforce  and  @spaceforcedod. The more we treat each other with dignity and respect, and ensure that this is a fundamental part of our culture, the higher we’ll rise together.

node.text:
As we honor Black History Month, I’d like to take a moment to share with you one of my favorite stories about Rosa Parks. I share this in hopes that when we think of civil rights exemplars such as Rosa Parks, the Tuskegee Airmen, Dr. Martin Luther King, and the many other pioneers of integration and racial equality, that we also reflect on ourselves. How can we better ourselves and understand that together we have an opportunity to become not only better Air and Space Forces, but a nation that champions diversity and inclusion?

node.text: It's the people that make #youracademy so special.  So says this week's #FirstieFriday, C1C Sierra Lyon.  Sierra hails from Hawaii and hopes to commission into the @spaceforcedod when she graduates in May.  When not in class completing her space operations degree, she's been playing on the club water polo team, taking photos of water polo and track, or busy with duties on the cadet group and wing staff.  And whenever she's home you'll find her surfing the waves off the north shore of Oahu.  #usafa2022

For many cadets at #youracademy, 9/11 and the start of the war in Afghanistan were before their time, but they are definitely at the forefront of their minds today. Cadets, faculty, and staff participated in an open forum to discuss the current situation in Afghanistan, its policy impact, share their stories, as well as the emotional impact on those who serve.
Combining current events with classroom learning is another way we develop leaders of character.

node.text:
Happy #FirstieFriday!

Wing Training Officer C1C Colin Jarrett-Izzi hails from San Antonio, TX and grew up in an Air Force family.

He's a Political Science Major with a French Minor and serves on the Academy Forensics Team. Colin would like to commission in OSI or Intel.

During survival training, he received quite the wake-up when a train passed by that was "far too close," which is one of his most memorable experiences at the Academy.

His advice to current cadets is to never lose touch with friends when changing squadrons or classes because they're the best friends you'll ever make and each one makes you stronger.

"Good leaders always have time to take care of their people." 

#YourAcademy

A Women's Legacy Memorial unveiled recently in Kokomo, IN includes the likeness of one of the Academy's own. 
Lt Col (ret) Shawna Rochelle Kimbrell, class of 1998 and Indiana native, is represented as one of three statues honoring women's contributions to country, family and community. 
The former fighter pilot hopes the memorial will help inspire young women to reach for their dreams.  Read more at https://tinyurl.com/ma6dvhfn
